Detected handwritten digits with CNNs

In this assignment, we Detected handwritten digits with CNNs. MNIST dataset includes 60,000 small square 2828 pixel grayscale images of handwritten single digits between 0 and 9. I created a simple CNN from scratch using the deep learning framework of your choice (Keras, TensorFlow) to perform classification on the MNIST dataset.

It includs the following steps: Created a base CNN model (Conv MaxPooling Flatten Dropout FC). Trained the model for 10 epochs using 10% for validation (batch_size=32, optimizer=Adam,dropout=0.5, activation=relu). Evaluated the performance of the model and reported the confusion matrix and the test accuracy. Evaluated the performance of the model with different batch sizes and different activation functions, reported the confusion matrix and the test accuracy.

Setup

Prepare the data

In[]:
# Model / data parameters
num_classes = 10
input_shape = (28, 28, 1)

# Load the data and split it between train and test sets
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = keras.datasets.mnist.load_data()

# Scale images to the [0, 1] range
x_train = x_train.astype("float32") / 255
x_test = x_test.astype("float32") / 255
# Make sure images have shape (28, 28, 1)
x_train = np.expand_dims(x_train, -1)
x_test = np.expand_dims(x_test, -1)
print("x_train shape:", x_train.shape)
print(x_train.shape[0], "train samples")
print(x_test.shape[0], "test samples")


# convert class vectors to binary class matrices
y_train = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes)
y_test = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes)

x_train shape: (60000, 28, 28, 1)
60000 train samples
10000 test samples

Build the model by adding 1 layer

In[]:
#build the model with 1 layer
name = '1_Layer_batch_sizes_32_relu'
model_1 = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.Input(shape=input_shape),
        keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
        keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
        keras.layers.Flatten(),
        keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax"),
    ], name=name
)

model_1.summary()

Confusion matrix of the model with 1 layer

In[]:
# Predict the values from the validation dataset
Y_pred = model_1.predict(x_test)
# Convert predictions classes to one hot vectors
Y_pred_classes = np.argmax(Y_pred,axis = 1)
# Convert validation observations to one hot vectors
Y_true = np.argmax(y_test,axis = 1)
# compute the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_true, Y_pred_classes)
print(cm)
# plot the confusion matrix
classes = range(10)
plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
plt.title('comfusion matrix of the model with 1 layer and batch sizes=32 and activation=relu')
plt.colorbar()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)
thresh = cm.max() / 2.
for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
    plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
        horizontalalignment="center",
        color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.savefig('./confusion_matrix_1_layer_batch_sizes_32_relu.jpg')

        keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),
        keras.layers.Flatten(),

        keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax"),
    ], name=name
)

#build the model with 1 layer and batch size=64 and activation=relu

        keras.layers.Flatten(),
        keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax"),
    ], name=name
)

#build the model with 1 layer and batch size=128
name = '1_Layer_batch_sizes_128_relu'
model_1_128 = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.Input(shape=input_shape),
        keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
        keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
        keras.layers.Flatten(),
        keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax"),
    ], name=name
)

model_1_128.summary()

batch_size = 128
epochs = 10
#compile the model
model_1_128.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])
#train the model
history_1_128 = model_1_128.fit(x_train, y_train, batch_size=batch_size, epochs=epochs, validation_split=0.1)
#save the train result
diff_batch_dict[model_1_128.name] = history_1_128

#Evaluate the trained model
score = model_1_128.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print("Test loss:", score[0])
print("Test accuracy:", score[1])

# Predict the values from the validation dataset
Y_pred = model_1_128.predict(x_test)
# Convert predictions classes to one hot vectors
Y_pred_classes = np.argmax(Y_pred,axis = 1)
# Convert validation observations to one hot vectors
Y_true = np.argmax(y_test,axis = 1)
# compute the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_true, Y_pred_classes)
print(cm)
# plot the confusion matrix
classes = range(10)
plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
plt.title('comfusion matrix of the model with 1 layer and batch sizes=128 and activation=relu')
plt.colorbar()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)
thresh = cm.max() / 2.
for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
    plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
        horizontalalignment="center",
        color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.savefig('./confusion_matrix_1_layer_batch_size_128_relu.jpg')

Plot the accuracy and loss of the model with different layers

In[]:
#Plot the accuracy and loss of the model with different layers
fig,(ax1,ax2)=plt.subplots(2,figsize=(8,8))
for history in history_dict:
    val_acc = history_dict[history].history['accuracy']
    val_loss = history_dict[history].history['val_loss']
    ax1.plot(val_acc, label=history)
    ax2.plot(val_loss, label=history)
ax1.set_ylabel('testing Accuracy')
ax2.set_ylabel('testing Loss')
ax1.set_xlabel('Epochs')
ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
ax1.set_title("The accuracy of the models with different layers")
ax2.set_title("The loss of the models with different layers")
ax1.legend()
ax2.legend()
plt.show()

Above figure showed that the model with 2 layers with the same batch sizes and the activate function had the best accuracy.

The difference between epoch and batch is:

The batch size is a number of samples processed before the model is updated. The size of a batch must be more than or equal to one and less than or equal to the number of samples in the training dataset.

The number of epochs is the number of complete passes through the training dataset. The number of epochs can be set to an integer value between one and infinity.

From the above figure(the accuracy and loss of the model with the same layers but different batch sizes), we can see that larger batch sizes take less time to train but are less accurate.

Max pooling is a pooling operation that selects the maximum element from the region of the feature map covered by the filter. Thus, the output after the max-pooling layer would be a feature map containing the most prominent features of the previous feature map.
